    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_152251300" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/152251300" />
    <a title="Marie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/220178-marie"><img alt="Marie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563489551p2/220178.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/152251300?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marie" href="/user/show/220178-marie">Marie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer152251300" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16177579294008449249">There are a lot of great things going on this book, but in the end if fell a bit flat for me, never fully capitalizing on what could have been so fulfilling. <br/><br/>Things I liked:<br/><br/>* the story is set in Venice in the 1500&apos;s, at the height of the city-state&apos;s power<br/>* the characters are unusual and interesting - a dwarf, a courtesan, a healer, and a cast of wealthy, corrupt Venetians/Romans<br/>* The storytelling is good - the writing is solid and the voice is true to the era<br/><br/>Things I didn&apos;t like:<br/><br/>* the story see</span>
  <span id="freeText16177579294008449249" style="display:none">There are a lot of great things going on this book, but in the end if fell a bit flat for me, never fully capitalizing on what could have been so fulfilling. <br /><br />Things I liked:<br /><br />* the story is set in Venice in the 1500's, at the height of the city-state's power<br />* the characters are unusual and interesting - a dwarf, a courtesan, a healer, and a cast of wealthy, corrupt Venetians/Romans<br />* The storytelling is good - the writing is solid and the voice is true to the era<br /><br />Things I didn't like:<br /><br />* the story seemed to have changed focus several times throughout the book. La Draga's identity and Bucino's last-minute change of heart seemed rather out of the blue to me, and the story ended not so much on Fiammetta's rise from the ashes or planning for her future, which was the original story line, but on La Draga and Bucino.<br />* even within the Bucino-La Draga story, I felt like so much went unanswered. <br />* there were long passages of unnecessary detail that I skimmed over, wanting to get to the point.<br />* Fiammetta and Arentino's relationship deserved more backstory.<br />* The part about Fiammetta and "the pup" seemed unnecessary - leading us to potential ruin, and then simply going away.<br /><br />So, I liked it, but didn't love it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16177579294008449249" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


